-- LLM evaluation:

  yield awkward-parts ≡ [
    "B1 (medium): Parallelism between simmer-sauce and cook-pasta is now implicit — neither references the other, so they run independently. But this isn't stated anywhere in the recipe. A cook reading linearly might think steps run sequentially by default. Severity: 2. Fix: minor — add a comment syntax or 'NOTE:' line, or accept that unlabeled independence is the convention.",
    "B2 (medium): 'parmesan 50 g OR nutritional-yeast 30 g' — amounts differ (50g vs 30g) but without RATIO the cook must just trust the recipe author. This is actually correct — the recipe author picked appropriate amounts for each. But losing explicit ratios means you can't scale proportionally. Severity: 1. Fix: acceptable trade-off — RATIO was more confusing than helpful.",
    "B3 (complex): IF-SUB tofu line works well now with ALONGSIDE rice. But 'IF-SUB tofu' checks for the ingredient name 'tofu', while the ingredients line says 'chicken 500 g OR tofu 400 g'. Is 'tofu' matched by name? What if the ingredient was 'firm-tofu'? Grammar doesn't define how IF-SUB matches ingredient names. Severity: 2. Fix: specify that IF-SUB matches the substitution ingredient name exactly as written in the OR clause."
  ]

  yield severity-scores ≡ [2, 1, 2]

  yield overall-score ≡ 1.67

  yield is-clean ≡ false

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ each severity-score ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} → ✓ (2, 1, 2)
--   ⊨ overall-score = mean of severity-scores → ✓ ((2+1+2)/3 = 1.67)
--   ⊨ if overall-score > 1.5 or max(severity-scores) ≥ 4 then is-clean = false
--     → ✓ (1.67 > 1.5, but max = 2 < 4; first condition triggers, is-clean = false)

-- state after frame 12: critique frozen (v2).
