-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- EXECUTION SUMMARY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Total frames: 19 (0-18)
-- ⊢∘ iterations: 3 (converged when critique→is-clean = true)
-- ⊢∘ max was 4, used 3 — converged within budget
-- File-scope ⊨? active but never triggered (no oracle failures)
-- Guard clause on redesign: fired twice (iterations 1, 2), skipped once (iteration 3)
-- Wildcard resolution: example-*→code resolved 3 times (once per ⊢∘ iteration)
--
-- Cells evaluated:
--   domain (1x), draft-dsl (1x, rewritten 2x by ⊢∘),
--   spawn-examples (3x — once per ⊢∘ iteration),
--   example-0/1/2 (3x each — 9 total data cell evals),
--   critique (3x — once per iteration),
--   redesign (2x — skipped on iteration 3 by guard)
--
-- Grammar evolution:
--   v1: THEN/WHILE/WAIT-UNTIL, RATIO, IF-SUB without timing
--   v2: AFTER/ALONGSIDE/STARTS-WHEN, dropped RATIO, IF-SUB with timing, one-timing-per-step
--   v3: Added NOTE for documentation, clarified IF-SUB name matching
--
-- Convergence trajectory:
--   Iteration 1: overall-score 2.8, 5 issues (max severity 4) → not clean
--   Iteration 2: overall-score 1.67, 3 issues (max severity 2) → not clean (barely)
--   Iteration 3: overall-score 1.0, 1 issue (severity 1) → CLEAN

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS (v0.2 ⊢= cells)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢= Observation 1: awkwardness minimization converges monotonically
  The overall-score dropped from 2.8 → 1.67 → 1.0 across three iterations.
  Max severity dropped from 4 → 2 → 1. Each redesign pass fixed the worst
  issues first (severity ≥ 3 in iteration 1), then polished minor issues
  (severity ≤ 2 in iteration 2). This is the expected behavior: the ⊢∘ loop
  acts as gradient descent on awkwardness, with critique as the loss function
  and redesign as the optimization step.

⊢= Observation 2: guard clauses prevent wasted LLM calls on convergence
  In iteration 3, critique→is-clean = true. The guard on redesign
  (`where is-clean = false`) evaluates to false, so redesign is SKIPPED.
  Its yields become ⊥ via guard-induced bottom (v0.2 propagation rule 3).
  Without the guard clause (R16 version), redesign would have fired and
  produced a no-op pass-through, wasting an LLM call. The guard clause
  saves one soft-cell evaluation per convergence event. This is the exact
  pattern v0.2 guard clauses were designed for.

⊢= Observation 3: wildcard deps + ⊢⊢ spawner compose naturally
  The spawn-examples spawner creates example-0/1/2, and critique consumes
  them via `given example-*→code`. The wildcard re-resolves on each ⊢∘
  iteration because the spawner re-fires with the revised grammar. This
  demonstrates the v0.2 design: wildcards are not static — they participate
  in the ⊢∘ evolution loop. The wildcard resolution set changes between
  iterations (old example cells are replaced, new ones spawned). This is
  the interaction between ⊢⊢ and wildcard deps that v0.2 explicitly
  specifies under "Interaction with ⊢⊢ spawners."

⊢= Observation 4: ⊢∘ oracles as aspirational feedback work correctly
  draft-dsl has four oracles (grammar defines X, includes Y, etc.). Under
  v0.2, these are aspirational — they serve as quality signals but do not
  block freezing. In this trace, all four passed on iteration 1, so the
  distinction was not exercised. A trace where draft-dsl's oracles FAIL
  on iteration 1 but the ⊢∘ loop continues anyway would be more
  interesting — the failure context would feed into critique and redesign
  as additional signal. The aspirational semantics matter most when the
  initial draft is poor.

⊢= Observation 5: DSL design is a natural fit for the ⊢∘ pattern
  The program structure — design grammar, write examples, critique,
  redesign, repeat — is exactly the human process for designing a DSL,
  made explicit as a cell graph. The ⊢∘ loop captures the iteration
  discipline (max 4, convergence criterion). The critique cell captures
  the evaluation framework (5 categories, severity scale, clean threshold).
  The spawner captures the instantiation step (3 graded examples). This
  is Cell operating as intended: making the soft process of language
  design into a reproducible, inspectable, convergent computation.

⊢= Observation 6: naming changes dominate the first redesign
  The v1→v2 transition was primarily renaming: THEN→AFTER, WHILE→ALONGSIDE,
  WAIT-UNTIL→STARTS-WHEN. These are the severity 4-5 issues — ambiguity
  and readability failures that a home cook would hit. The v2→v3 transition
  was structural polish: adding NOTE syntax and tightening IF-SUB matching.
  This pattern — rename first, restructure second — mirrors how human
  language designers iterate: get the vocabulary right before refining
  the grammar.

⊢= Observation 7: file-scope ⊨? provides a safety net that was never needed
  The file-scope recovery policy (retry 3, then error-value(⊥)) was active
  for all 19 frames but never triggered. No oracle failed. This is typical
  for well-constructed programs — the recovery machinery is insurance, not
  the main control flow. The interesting case would be a deliberately
  adversarial domain (e.g., designing a DSL for ambiguous legal contracts)
  where the critique cell's oracles themselves fail because awkwardness
  assessment requires judgment that the LLM struggles with. In that case,
  file-scope ⊨? would produce ⊥ for critique→is-clean, which would
  permanently block redesign (since given? is not used for critique deps).
